title: For Sale:  Wards Western Field
location: North End, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent: This is a Wards Western Field Model 35 12 ga pump action shotgun.  From the information I have collected, it was designed by John Browning and sold to the Stevens company who manufactured the Stevens 520.  They also made some for Montgomery Wards who rebranded them the Western Field.  This shotgun was manufactured between 1933 and 1935.  It may be the delux edition since it does have the recoil pad on the end of the butt stock.  It has a smooth barrel and a poly choke.  It is in working condition and does fire, but someone replaced the ejector screw, it is missing the breech block forward stop screw, and the shell stop spring is also missing so you cannot load more than one shell in the magazine tube.  The finish is not perfect and the stock shows wear.  There is also a chip in the stock where it attaches to the receiver.  This shotgun has been used and does show its age, but it is still a great old gun that would be a great addition for someone who is into older firearms or who is looking to have one just like their grandpa did back in the day.  As far as the value, I have seen estimates up in the range of $300 for ones in good condition.  I have set the price at $125 based on the missing stop spring and the fact that it is not in great condition.  I have seen the stop spring for sale for $40 on another website.  I also listed the manufacturer as Browning since Stevens was not an option and it was originally designed by Browning.

title: For Sale:  AR15 in .223 Wylde, The Ultimate Light Weight 3 gun rifle, under 5lbs!
postcontent: This was my no expense spared, exactly what I want, best in class rifle for 3 gun and tactical rifle competitions and served that role well. Right up until I got hurt and am not doing any running and gunning for a while. The barrel is a super light weight Faxon 16" (weighs less than carbon fiber barrels) with at titanium gas block and tube, and Fortis RED muzzle device. It is lapped and bedded to an F1 billet upper running a lightweight NibX coated skeletonized BCG with JP bolt. The lower is a Ghost Industies Skeletonized lower built with Titanium internals (castle nut, back plate, take down pins, buffer pin, etc) and a POF 3.5lb pull Skeleton trigger unit. The grip is a Houge lightweight unit that still gives great feel, with a BCM polymer trigger guard. The buffer spring is JP and the buffer is a low mass unit. Also has Seekins enhanced bolt and mage release, and ambex safety. This awesome rifle weighs under 5lbs unloaded and shoots around or under MOA with about every decent ammo I have ran through it. It was originally a sub 4 1/2 pound rifle, but I decided I would trade a few ounces for some livability. However to get it back to just over 4lbs is a simple swap of 3 components. A few questions I always get on this (and it will draw attention at the range):Q: Don't you get gas in your face? A: No, it has a properly regulated gas system and the cuts on the upper are angled away from the shooter.Q: Is the recoil horrible? A: It is probably the lightest shooting AR I have ever owned. This is due to the well regulated gas system, low reciprocating mass and muzzle device. It feels more like a 22 that a 5.56. Q: Does it get dirty quickly or jam? A: In a word, no. The internals are all NP3 or Titatnium, so you just have to wipe them down every thousand rounds or so, and  that is mainly to keep them shiny. You can literally clean it with a garden hose and canned air it dry.Q: Is it ammunition sensitive? A: Nope. I have fired everything from Wolf steel case to 77 grain premium defense with zero issues or failures.Q: How much do you have wrapped up in it? A: I stopped counting at $1800, so north of that. F2F with VA resident non-felons withing 45 minutes of Charlottesville. Not interested in trades at this time unless you have a Tanfoglio Limited or Stock II/III or a Czech Mate in 9mm or .40.
